"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49418","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-05-08","<p>The Competition Commission's cost for the inquiry into the proposed merger between Royal Bournemouth and Christchurch Hospitals Foundation Trust and Poole Hospital Foundation Trust was Â£710,000. This amount includes the cost of the staff on the inquiry amounting to Â£639,000 and direct costs of Â£71,000 (including survey costs).</p>","Cardiff Central","Jenny Willott",,"2014-05-08T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49418/answer","Biography information for Jenny Willott","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49418/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the cost of the Competition Commission's inquiry into the proposed merger between Royal Bournemouth and Christchurch Hospitals Foundation Trust and Poole Hospital Foundation Trust.","false","Biography information for Liz Kendall","Leicester West","Liz Kendall","197575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49419","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-05-07","<p>The Government will keep the 15 year time limit under consideration, but is not minded to change the law at the present time.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-05-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49419/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49419/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, whether the Government plans to increase the 15 year out-of-country voting limit for British expatriates.","false","Biography information for Simon Danczuk","Rochdale","Simon Danczuk","197545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49420","Home Office","false","2014-05-14","<p> </p><p>Foreign national students who had been served with an adverse immigration <br>decision were, at times, encountering a delay in receiving their travel <br>documents back from the Home Office. On occasion this resulted in their <br>immigration status changing to an overstayer. <br><br>The pilot referred to was conducted through an informal relationship between <br>the South Central Immigration Compliance and Enforcement (ICE) team and the <br>International Student Advisors embedded within two local Universities. Through <br>this link, those whose leave has been curtailed, have had an adverse decision, <br>or wish to depart the UK are provided with local assistance by the Immigration <br>Enforcement team. The pilot has enabled the local ICE team to facilitate the <br>return of travel documents quickly, resulting in an earlier departure for the <br>student. This has benefits for both the student and University as becoming an <br>overstayer could jeopardise future applications from students to continue their <br>studies. During 2013/14, fifty students were assisted in this way from two <br>Universities (this is local data taken from local records that has not been <br>sourced from an official database).<br><br>The Government is looking at how this example of local good practice can be <br>extended nationally.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-05-14T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49420/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49420/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49420/answer/previousversion/8887","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 28 April 2014, Official Report, columns 526-7, on student visas, if she will publish details of the successful pilot with one university on ensuring overseas students return home once their course is completed.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Mr Frank Field","197624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49421","Department of Health","false","2014-05-08","<p>The Child Protection â Information Sharing (CP-IS) project will allow the sharing of child protection information between National Health Service unscheduled care settings and local authority children's services staff only. The information will not be shared with care homes or the police.</p><p> </p><p>CP-IS will hold child protection information only for children in England who are subject to a child protection plan or are looked after by a local authority.</p><p> </p><p>When NHS staff submit a query the CP-IS service, the system will electronically share the following information with the local authority responsible for the child: the time and date of the query, the name of the NHS healthcare worker who made the query, and the NHS organisation from within which the query was made.</p><p> </p><p>CP-IS will not introduce information sharing over and beyond what is currently shared by NHS staff and local authorities.</p><p> </p><p>The Health and Social Care Information Centre has published guidance on its website for NHS and local authority staff on how to use the CP-IS system.</p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-05-08T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49421/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49421/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance his Department will provide for NHS staff on whether to share the information on the Child Protection Information Sharing project with relevant local authorities, police forces or care homes.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","197544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49422","Department for Education","false","2014-05-07","<p>ContactPoint was discontinued because it was disproportionate.</p><p>The Government believes it is unjustifiable to hold information on every child in England and to make it accessible to hundreds of thousands of people.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-05-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49422/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49422/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, for what reasons the Contact Point database was discontinued.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","197558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49423","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-05-07","<p>The Cultural Passport scheme was launched as âArtsbox' in February of this year. The programme is run independently of DCMS by Trinity College London, and therefore the Department does not hold the information requested. DCMS welcomes this initiative which allows children and young people to share their creative work.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-05-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49423/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49423/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many and what proportion of pupils in each age group participate in the Cultural Passport scheme; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","197570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49424","Department for Education","false","2014-05-07","<p>The Department for Education does not collect data on the number or proportion of schools in England providing the minimum level of cultural education proposed in Appendix A of Cultural Education: a summary of programmes and opportunities. Nor does the Department collect data on what proportion of pupils, of any age, have received the minimum level of cultural education it proposes.</p><p> </p><p>The levels of cultural education the Appendix proposes are not mandatory, but are included as a point of reference for schools.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","197609","2014-05-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49424/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49424/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of schools in England provide the minimum level of cultural education proposed in Appendix A of Cultural Education: a summary of programmes and opportunities, published in July 2013; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","197608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49425","Department for Education","false","2014-05-07","<p>The Department for Education does not collect data on the number or proportion of schools in England providing the minimum level of cultural education proposed in Appendix A of Cultural Education: a summary of programmes and opportunities. Nor does the Department collect data on what proportion of pupils, of any age, have received the minimum level of cultural education it proposes.</p><p> </p><p>The levels of cultural education the Appendix proposes are not mandatory, but are included as a point of reference for schools.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","197608","2014-05-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49425/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49425/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of pupils aged (a) seven, (b) 11, (c) 16 and (d) 18 or 19 years have received the minimum level of cultural education proposed in Appendix A of Cultural Education: a summary of programmes and opportunities, published in July 2013; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","197609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49426","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-05-07","<p>Since the abduction of the Nigerian school girls on 14 April, we have focused our efforts on working with the Nigerian Government to locate and secure the release of the girls. We have made no representations to UN Women about the case. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Richmond (Yorks) (Mr Hague) made a statement condemning the schoolgirls abduction on 16 April.</p>","Boston and Skegness","Mark Simmonds",,"2014-05-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49426/answer","Biography information for Mark Simmonds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49426/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with UN Women about the abduction of schoolgirls from Chibok in north-eastern Nigeria on 14 April 2014; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","197532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49427","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-05-07","<p>Since the abduction of the Nigerian school girls on 14 April, we have focused our efforts on working with the Nigerian government to locate and secure the release of the girls. We have discussed the issue with officials from counterpart members of the UN Security Council in New York. On 7 May, I spoke with UN Special Representatives (SR), Zainab Bangura (UN SR for Sexual Violence) and Leila Zeroughi (UN SR for Children and Armed Conflict), to discuss what more the UN can do to help.</p>","Boston and Skegness","Mark Simmonds",,"2014-05-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49427/answer","Biography information for Mark Simmonds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49427/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to (a) the UN and (b) any UN agency on the abduction of schoolgirls from Chibok in north-eastern Nigeria on 14 April 2014.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","197520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49428","Department of Health","false","2014-05-12","<p>All existing contracts for stereotactic radiotherapy services were transferred to NHS England on 1 April 2013 and it continues to commission against these contracts, as previously.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England commenced the review of stereotactic radiosurgery in August 2013 and expects a final report to be considered at its specialised commissioning oversight group, post a public consultation period, in October 2014.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England will consult with the public, patients and professionals and take account of those views when taking a final decision. A summary of the responses received will be included when publishing the final report post the consultation period.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","197487 ; 197488","2014-05-12T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49428/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49428/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to section 2 of the guidance issued by Monitor on the Commissioning of Radiosurgery Services on 4 April 2014, if he will request that NHS England reinstates the commissioning of stereotactic radiotherapy to the level before 1 April 2013 while it conducts its review into the future use of this treatment.","false","Biography information for Tessa Munt","Wells","Tessa Munt","197559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49429","Department of Health","false","2014-05-12","<p>All existing contracts for stereotactic radiotherapy services were transferred to NHS England on 1 April 2013 and it continues to commission against these contracts, as previously.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England commenced the review of stereotactic radiosurgery in August 2013 and expects a final report to be considered at its specialised commissioning oversight group, post a public consultation period, in October 2014.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England will consult with the public, patients and professionals and take account of those views when taking a final decision. A summary of the responses received will be included when publishing the final report post the consultation period.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","197488 ; 197559","2014-05-12T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49429/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49429/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will publish (a) a list of all stakeholders who have so far been consulted by NHS England as part of its review into stereotactic radiosurgery and (b) the responses from those stakeholders.","false","Biography information for Tessa Munt","Wells","Tessa Munt","197487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49430","Department of Health","false","2014-05-12","<p>All existing contracts for stereotactic radiotherapy services were transferred to NHS England on 1 April 2013 and it continues to commission against these contracts, as previously.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England commenced the review of stereotactic radiosurgery in August 2013 and expects a final report to be considered at its specialised commissioning oversight group, post a public consultation period, in October 2014.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England will consult with the public, patients and professionals and take account of those views when taking a final decision. A summary of the responses received will be included when publishing the final report post the consultation period.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","197487 ; 197559","2014-05-12T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49430/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49430/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when NHS England began its review into the future of stereotactic radiosurgery; and when its plans to complete the review.","false","Biography information for Tessa Munt","Wells","Tessa Munt","197488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49431","Home Office","false","2014-05-13","<p> </p><p>I wrote to the Hon. Member. on 12 May. A copy of the letter was also placed in <br>the House Library. <br><br>The MPs' hotline is a dedicated resource, for Members, based in Croydon and <br>answers queries on Members' constituents' immigration queries. The staffing <br>costs of the MPs' hotline for 2013 were Â£180,240.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-05-13T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49431/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49431/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the annual cost is of the asylum and immigration hotline open to hon. Members.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","197460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49432","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-05-07","<p> </p><p> </p><p>The information requested is available up to December 2013 and can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Stat-Xplore_User_Guide.htm" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Stat-Xplore_User_Guide.htm</a></p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-05-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49432/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49432/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the number of applicants who seek a national insurance number and claim welfare benefits within six months of receipt.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","197459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49433","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-05-14","<p> </p><p> </p><p>The National Offender Management Service (NOMS) takes the issue of mobile phones in prisons very seriously and is committed to addressing the risks they present to both the security of prisons and the safety of the public.</p><p> </p><p>NOMS has implemented a multi-layered approach: to minimise the number of mobile phones entering prisons, to find phones that do get in and to disrupt mobile phones that cannot be found. A range of technology has been rolled out to prisons to strengthen searching and security, including portable mobile phone signal detectors, Body Orifice Security Scanners (BOSS chairs), high sensitivity metal detecting wands and short range portable mobile phone blockers.</p><p> </p><p>The adjudication process exists to allow prison governors to deal with breaches of prison discipline, including possession of unauthorised items such as mobile telephones.</p><p> </p><p>From centrally held data, it is not possible to identify those offenders who breached prison discipline by possessing a mobile phone, were proceeded against and given the punishment of additional days. The prison adjudication offence details held centrally are not of sufficient detail to identify the specific breach item - mobile phone possession offences are grouped with other prohibited items.</p><p> </p><p>Determining if the requested information is held would require a manual search through all individual prison records where a breach of prison discipline led to adjudication in respect of possession of a prohibited item to see if any information is recorded on the type of item. Inspecting each record to ascertain if there was an adjudication for possession of a mobile phone and how many additional days were given as a punishment could only be done at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-05-14T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49433/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49433/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, on how many times the offence of possession of mobile telephones within a prison has been proceeded upon; and how many days were added to the offender's sentence in each case.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","197533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49434","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-05-07","<p /> <p /> <p>We have interpreted the question to be for the number of Jobseeker's Allowance (JSA) claimants who were sanctioned and this information is published and can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Stat-Xplore_User_Guide.htm" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Stat-Xplore_User_Guide.htm</a></p><p> </p><p>The information requested on how many JSA claimants continued to sign on during the period for which they were sanctioned is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-05-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49434/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49434/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many benefit claimants were sanctioned in each month since August 2013; and how many such claimants continued to sign on during the period for which they were sanctioned.","false","Biography information for Mr Michael Meacher","Oldham West and Royton","Mr Michael Meacher","197517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49435","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-05-07","<p> </p><p>The Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Natural Environment and Science has met a number of interested bodies to discuss what action can be taken to address fly grazing in England. There is a range of legislation that can be used depending on the individual circumstances of each case. Most of the problems associated with fly grazing are linked to difficulties in tracing owners of unidentified horses. In such cases we would encourage a joined-up approach by enforcers and interested parties at a local level to help tackle the problem. It is already an offence under the Horse Passport Regulations for horses not to be identified. These regulations are enforced by local authorities. Fly grazing in Wales is a matter for the Welsh Government.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","197576 ; 197577 ; 197607","2014-05-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49435/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49435/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of changes in levels of fly-grazing in England following changes to relevant legislation in Wales.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","197603"
