"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49437","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-05-07","<p> </p><p>The Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Natural Environment and Science has met a number of interested bodies to discuss what action can be taken to address fly grazing in England. There is a range of legislation that can be used depending on the individual circumstances of each case. Most of the problems associated with fly grazing are linked to difficulties in tracing owners of unidentified horses. In such cases we would encourage a joined-up approach by enforcers and interested parties at a local level to help tackle the problem. It is already an offence under the Horse Passport Regulations for horses not to be identified. These regulations are enforced by local authorities. Fly grazing in Wales is a matter for the Welsh Government.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","197577 ; 197603 ; 197607","2014-05-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49437/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49437/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will assess the potential benefits of more stringent equine passport controls; and if he will bring forward legislative proposals to reverse the burden of proof and increase data-gathering on horse ownership in relation to fly-grazing.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","197576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49438","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-05-07","<p> </p><p>The Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Natural Environment and Science has met a number of interested bodies to discuss what action can be taken to address fly grazing in England. There is a range of legislation that can be used depending on the individual circumstances of each case. Most of the problems associated with fly grazing are linked to difficulties in tracing owners of unidentified horses. In such cases we would encourage a joined-up approach by enforcers and interested parties at a local level to help tackle the problem. It is already an offence under the Horse Passport Regulations for horses not to be identified. These regulations are enforced by local authorities. Fly grazing in Wales is a matter for the Welsh Government.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","197576 ; 197603 ; 197607","2014-05-07T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49438/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/49438/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-05-01","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of current legislation against fly-grazing.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","197577"
